   Defense Secretary-designate John Tower contradicted an earlier sworn statement when he told the Senate his work for a British firm involved no military matters, according to reports published Saturday.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   In written testimony to the Senate panel on Jan. 26, Tower said he could ``recall no actions in connection with any defense activities'' in connection with his work for the U.S. subsidiary of British Aerospace, Inc.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   The New York Post reported Saturday that the FBI apparently has not bothered to talk to Tower's neighbors, examine certain police records or investigate several car accidents involving Tower.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   On Friday, Tower authorized the release of a statement that recent hospital tests showed no evidence of alcohol abuse, and Vice President Dan Quayle said, ``I have never seen drinking being a factor in John Tower's life other than a social glass of wine''.
